Title: The Gift of the Magi
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: O. Henry's short story (1905, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026

====

FADE IN:

INT. DELLA & JIM'S FLAT - AFTERNOON

A small, shabby-genteel apartment. DELLA (20s) sits counting coins on the table, again and again, as if recounting might change the total. One dollar and eighty-seven cents. Sixty of it in pennies.

DELLA
(to herself, near tears)
One eighty-seven. And tomorrow is Christmas.

She catches her reflection in a cheap mirror between the windows -- long, beautiful hair, her one great vanity, tumbling past her waist.

She stares at it a long moment. Then, decision made, she pulls on her old brown jacket and shabby hat.

CUT TO:

INT. MADAME SOFRONIE'S HAIR SHOP - CONTINUOUS

MADAME SOFRONIE, cool and businesslike, lifts a length of Della's hair, appraising.

MADAME SOFRONIE
Twenty dollars.

DELLA
(quiet, resolved)
Give it to me quick.

CUT TO:

EXT. CITY STREETS - LATER

Della, hair cropped short and curled close to her head, moves quickly from shop to shop, searching. She finds it at last -- a platinum watch fob chain, simple and dignified, worthy of Jim's one prized possession: his grandfather's gold watch.

SHOPKEEPER
Twenty-one dollars, miss.

DELLA
(handing over her money)
I'll take it.

CUT TO:

INT. DELLA & JIM'S FLAT - LATE AFTERNOON

Della curls what's left of her hair with tongs before a mirror, trying to make herself presentable.

DELLA
(to her reflection, wry)
If Jim doesn't kill me before he takes a second look, he'll say I look like a Coney Island chorus girl.

She hears footsteps on the stair and blows out the lamp on the table, suddenly anxious.

DELLA (CONT'D)
(murmuring, half a prayer)
Please God, make him think I am still pretty.

The door opens. JIM (young, careworn beyond his years, thin) enters, stopping dead at the sight of her.

He stares -- an expression Della cannot read. Not anger. Not approval. Something unreadable and fixed.

DELLA (CONT'D)
(rushing, nervous)
Jim, darling, don't look at me that way. I had my hair cut off and sold, because I couldn't have lived through Christmas without giving you a present. It'll grow back -- say "Merry Christmas," Jim, and let's be happy.

JIM
(slowly)
You've cut off your hair?

DELLA
Cut it off and sold it. Don't you like me just as well? I'm me without my hair, aren't I?

Jim looks around the room as if searching for someone.

JIM
You say your hair is gone?

DELLA
You needn't look for it. It's sold, I tell you -- sold and gone, too. It's Christmas Eve, boy. Be good to me, for it went for you.

Jim seems to shake off a daze at last and embraces her.

JIM
(gently)
Don't make any mistake about me, Della. I don't think there's anything could make me like my girl any less. But if you'll unwrap that package, you may see why you had me going a while.

He hands her a small package. Della tears it open -- a set of ornamental combs, pure tortoise shell, the very ones she'd admired in a shop window for a year, meant for her now-cropped hair.

Della clutches them to her chest and bursts into tears.

DELLA
(through tears)
My hair grows so fast, Jim!

She leaps up suddenly, remembering.

DELLA (CONT'D)
Oh! I nearly forgot!

She hands Jim the small box holding the platinum chain.

DELLA (CONT'D)
Isn't it a beauty, Jim? I hunted all over town to find it. You'll have to look at the time a hundred times a day now.

Jim doesn't take the watch from his pocket. Instead he sits down on the couch, smiling strangely, and puts his hands behind his head.

JIM
Della, let's put our Christmas presents away and keep 'em a while. They're too nice to use just at present.

DELLA
(confused)
Why, Jim?

JIM
(quiet, a little rueful)
I sold the watch to get the money to buy your combs.

They sit together in the small, cooling apartment -- combs with no hair to hold, a chain with no watch to hang from -- and, after a moment, begin to laugh.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The magi, as you know, were wise men -- wonderfully wise men -- who brought gifts to the Christ child. They invented the art of giving. And here I have told you the story of two foolish children who most unwisely sacrificed the greatest treasures of their house for each other. But of all who give gifts, these two were the wisest. Everywhere, they are the wisest. They are the magi.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
